[{"id":"VR868606","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">Show all your work for each part of the question. The parts within the question may not have equal weight.</p><br/><div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Three figures are shown, labeled Figure 1 through Figure 3. Figure 1 shows the top view of a spring at the bottom of the figure in between the ends of a bar and a rod of negligible mass attached to a shared pivot, which is at the top of the figure. There is a sphere attached to the end of the rod of negligible mass. In Figure 2, the bar and the rod move apart so that the spring is now uncompressed. In Figure 3, the bar and the rod have moved so that they form a straight line with an angle of 180 degrees between them at the pivot. The bar points slightly upward and to the left, and the rod with the sphere at its end points slightly downward and to the left. A note indicates that the figures are not drawn to scale.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR868606.g02.svg\"/></div>\n<p class=\"passage_para\">Figures <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span> are top views of a system that can rotate in a horizontal plane about a vertical axis through a fixed pivot. One end of a uniform, thin bar is attached to the pivot, as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>. A small sphere is attached to a rod of negligible mass, and the other end of the rod is attached to the pivot. A compressed spring is between the sphere and the free end of the bar, and the bar and sphere are initially held in place.</p>\n<p class=\"passage_para\">The bar has mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M\"><math alttext=\"M\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>M</mi></math></span></span>, length <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"l\"><math alttext=\"l\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>ℓ</mo></math></span></span>, and rotational inertia <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"one third M times l squared\"><math alttext=\"one third M times l squared\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>M</mi><msup><mo>ℓ</mo><mn>2</mn></msup></math></span></span> about the pivot. The sphere has the same mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M\"><math alttext=\"M\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>M</mi></math></span></span> as the bar, and its center is a fixed distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"l\"><math alttext=\"l\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>ℓ</mo></math></span></span> from the pivot.</p>\n<p class=\"passage_para\">At time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lowercase t equals 0\"><math alttext=\"lowercase t equals 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></span></span>, the bar and sphere are released, after which the bar and rod start rotating with negligible friction about the pivot point, as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>. At a later time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lowercase t sub 1\"><math alttext=\"lowercase t sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>, shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span>, the bar and rod are <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"180\"><math alttext=\"180\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>180</mn></math></span></span> degrees apart. At <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lowercase t equals lowercase t sub 1\"><math alttext=\"lowercase t equals lowercase t sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>, a mechanism locks the bar and rod together so that they maintain a relative angle of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"180\"><math alttext=\"180\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>180</mn></math></span></span> degrees, but are still free to rotate about the pivot as a unit.</p>\n</div></div></div></div><div class=\"item_part part_id:Ai part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"Ai\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a) <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\"></span></p><ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\"><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\">i. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Indicate</span> whether the bar-rod-sphere system rotates clockwise, counterclockwise, or not at all after the mechanism has locked the bar and rod together. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Justify</span> your answer.</p></li></ul></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR868606_rubric"},{"id":"VR868606","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:Aii part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"Aii\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Assume that the bar and rod are approximately parallel at <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lowercase t equals 0\"><math alttext=\"lowercase t equals 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></span></span> and that the spring takes a very short amount of time to push them apart.</p><ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\"><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\">ii. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Derive</span> the value of the angle <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta sub B\"><math alttext=\"theta sub B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>θ</mi><mtext>B</mtext></msub></math></span></span> through which the <span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">bar</span> rotates from its starting position to where the bar and rod become locked together.</p></li></ul></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR868606_rubric"},{"id":"VR868606","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:B part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"B\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The spring that causes the initial separation of the two pieces exerts a force on each piece for a short time interval <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Zero is less than or equal to lowercase t, which is less than or equal to lowercase t sub 1\"><math alttext=\"Zero is less than or equal to lowercase t, which is less than or equal to lowercase t sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>0</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>≤</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>, after which the sphere has an angular speed <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"omega sub S\"><math alttext=\"omega sub S\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>ω</mi><mtext>S</mtext></msub></math></span></span>. The force results in a torque about the pivot, and the magnitude <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"tau\"><math alttext=\"tau\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>τ</mi></math></span></span> of the torque exerted on the sphere by the spring, as a function of time, can be modeled by the following equation:</p><p class=\"standalone_statement style:1\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"tau equals, open bracket, tau sub 0, end subscript, times the cosine of open parenthesis, the fraction with numerator pi times lowercase t, and denominator 2 lowercase t sub 1, end sub, end fraction, close parenthesis, for 0 less than equal to lowercase t, less than or equal to lowercase t sub 1, end sub; 0 otherwise\"><math alttext=\"tau equals, open bracket, tau sub 0, end subscript, times the cosine of open parenthesis, the fraction with numerator pi times lowercase t, and denominator 2 lowercase t sub 1, end sub, end fraction, close parenthesis, for 0 less than equal to lowercase t, less than or equal to lowercase t sub 1, end sub; 0 otherwise\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi>τ</mi><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo>{</mo><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>τ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>cos</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>π</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>)</mo></mrow></mtd><mtd><mtext>for</mtext><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mn>0</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>≤</mo><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mtext>otherwise</mtext></mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span></p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">where <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"tau sub 0\"><math alttext=\"tau sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>τ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mstyle></math></span></span> is a positive constant.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Derive</span> an expression for <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lowercase t sub 1\"><math alttext=\"lowercase t sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>t</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span> in terms of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"l\"><math alttext=\"l\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>ℓ</mo></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M\"><math alttext=\"M\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>M</mi></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"tau sub 0\"><math alttext=\"tau sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>τ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"omega sub S\"><math alttext=\"omega sub S\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>ω</mi><mtext>S</mtext></msub></math></span></span>, and physical constants, as appropriate.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR868606_rubric"}]